Part 1

The company had no office in this state yet, only a name that meant nothing here and a folder of licenses waiting to be argued over.

So they'd put him up wherever the local team could arrange affordably, which turned out to be a farmhouse on a hillside outside town, half orchard, half nothing at all, jungle pressing close on the far edge of the coffee plants.

Vikram arrived alone except for a driver he'd already forgotten the name of, and a suitcase not made for these roads.

Ramanna kept the place — an old man with a torch that flickered more than it lit, a dhoti pressed into permanent wrinkles, and a habit of calling every guest "sir" in a tone that made the word sound like a question.

"Board members usually don't come themselves," Ramanna said, unlocking the one guest room. "They send juniors."

"I'm the junior," Vikram said.

Ramanna looked at him properly for the first time, decided something privately, and said nothing further about it.

---

The room smelled of the last rain, and the one before that.

Vikram lay listening to sounds a city never let him hear — some insect working continuously at nothing, a dog somewhere deciding against barking at the last moment, the particular creak old wood makes when it's simply cooling for the night.

Sleep didn't come easily anymore, not since Ira, not since board meetings started depending on which way one minister's mood tilted on a given morning.

He got up for water near midnight and saw the fire.

Not close. Past the coffee rows, at the edge where the plantation gave up and the jungle properly began, a small flame moved the way flames only move when someone keeps feeding them.

A figure sat beside it, motionless except for one arm rising and falling in some rhythm Vikram couldn't place from this distance — throwing something into the fire, or gathering something from it, he couldn't tell which.

He watched longer than he meant to.

---

At breakfast — curd rice, a pickle sharp enough to clear his head faster than the coffee did — Vikram asked Ramanna who lit fires past the plantation at night.

Ramanna didn't look up from the vessel he was scrubbing.

"Aghori Baba."

"Someone from the village?"

"From nowhere, sir. From the jungle. Comes some nights, not others. Nobody invited him, and nobody's told him to leave, so." Ramanna shrugged, a gesture that closed the subject more firmly than any sentence could have.

"What does he do out there?"

"Whatever Aghoris do." Ramanna finally looked up. "You want my advice, sir? Don't go and ask him. He'll tell you. That's the trouble with him. He always tells you."

Vikram laughed — the first time in longer than he could place exactly.

He didn't take the advice.
